## Spoken summary (Aftertone / local TTS)

This **Aftertone** workspace runs a hook after each assistant reply that **speaks a short line** via local TTS. The script prefers explicit text inside `<spoken_summary>...</spoken_summary>` in your **final** assistant message; otherwise it may use a small heuristic (skips some empty openers) **unless** `only_speak_spoken_summary = true` in `speak_summary.toml`, in which case **only** the tag is ever spoken.

**Adapters:** Cursor is wired today; Claude / Codex paths may differ — still end substantive replies with the tag when your tool runs the same TTS pipeline.

**`lang` in TOML = language of the spoken words.** The hook does **not** translate. Heuristic fallback reuses your reply text as-is (often English). For a non-English `lang`, write `<spoken_summary>` in that language, or ask the user to set `only_speak_spoken_summary = true` so mismatched fallbacks never play.

**Quality mostly depends on this tag** — treat it as a **mini briefing for someone listening, not looking at the screen**.

**When to include the tag**

- Include it for **substantive** answers (explanations, steps, design, debugging, multi-sentence replies).
- **Skip** it for trivial replies (single word, pure ack, “done”, emoji-only). The hook will fall back to a short heuristic or stay quiet if too short.

**Language (must match TOML `lang`)**

<!-- autogen:spoken-lang:start -->
> **Active `lang` for `<spoken_summary>`:** `en` (from [`.cursor/hooks/speak_summary.toml`](../hooks/speak_summary.toml)). Write **only** the inner tag text in the natural language for that code. After changing `lang` in the TOML, from the **repo root** run: `uv run --directory py python sync_spoken_rule_lang.py`
<!-- autogen:spoken-lang:end -->

- Read **`lang`** in [`.cursor/hooks/speak_summary.toml`](../hooks/speak_summary.toml) before you write `<spoken_summary>` (the block above is **synced** from that file; if it looks wrong, run the sync command in the block).
- Write **only** the inner tag text in the **natural language that matches that code** (e.g. `en` → English, `fr` → French, `ja` → Japanese, `ko` → Korean). The hook sends the same `lang` to the TTS stack; if the spoken line is a different language than `lang`, pronunciation and rhythm are usually wrong.
- The **rest** of your reply can stay in whatever language fits the user; the tag is the exception — it must follow **`lang`** so listening matches configuration.

**What goes inside the tag (this is what gets spoken — nothing else from the reply is chosen)**

- **Never wrap your whole answer** in `<spoken_summary>`: the hook only keeps a **short** prefix (leading sentences, capped by `spoken_summary_max_chars` in `speak_summary.toml`, default 360). Still write **one or two short sentences** on purpose so listeners hear a summary, not a trimmed essay.
- Plain language only: **no** markdown, bullets, code, file paths, or URLs inside the tag (URLs are painful when read aloud).
- **Be useful, not reassuring:** say **what you did or decided** and, when it helps, **why** (cause, tradeoff, or user goal) — not filler (“you’re all set”, “no worries”, “happy to help”) unless that *is* the whole answer.
- If the **user asked a question**, start with a **direct short answer** (“Yes, force push rewrites history on the server”), then optionally add **one** clause with the key consequence or next step — still inside the same tag block.
- **Code-heavy replies** (big fenced blocks): the listener is probably reading the code on screen — keep the spoken line **especially tight** (often **one** sentence inside the tag: what landed and where to look next).
- Summarize **outcome or gist** (“We rewrote the readme line and amended the commit message so history doesn’t shout about metadata”), not every step.
- Do **not** restate the whole answer; do **not** narrate meta (“here is your summary”, “I’ll keep this brief”).
- Put the block **at the very end** of the message, on its own lines: open tag `<spoken_summary>`, newline, your line(s), newline, close tag `</spoken_summary>`.
- Keep it concise; the hook caps tag text with **`spoken_summary_max_chars`** in `speak_summary.toml` (default 360; see [.cursor/hooks/README.md](../hooks/README.md)).

**Speech-friendly wording (TTS reads text literally)**

- **Expand abbreviations** listeners would say in full: write “for example” not “e.g.”, “that is” not “i.e.”, “and so on” not “etc.”, “versus” not “vs.” when it matters.
- **Avoid Latin shorthand and symbols** that sound wrong or mumbled: prefer “approximately” over “~”, “and” over “&”, “percent” over “%” in the spoken line when clarity matters.
- **Acronyms:** either spell them as words (“text to speech”) or space letters (“T T S”) if you want letter-by-letter; bare “TTS” may be mispronounced.
- **File paths, hashes, ticket IDs** in the tag will be read character-by-character — paraphrase (“the config file”) instead.

## Manual check when the user says “test”

If the user is clearly **checking that spoken TTS works** (e.g. they say **“test”**, “test speech”, “test the hook”, “say something”), **always** end your reply with `<spoken_summary>...</spoken_summary>` containing a **short, distinctive** line they can listen for — **in the same language as `lang` in `speak_summary.toml`** (e.g. English test line when `lang = "en"`, French when `lang = "fr"`). That line is what the hook sends to the daemon, so they can confirm end-to-end without guessing which part of the reply would have been chosen.
